name: Mzimba, Livingstone N.
misc card notes: Fr to graduate from seminary 1909; returned home as Presbyterian minister, Presbyterian Church of Africa; was sent by father, Umfundisi Pambani Jeremiah Mzimba, along with six other young men, to become a leadership for the Presbyterian Church of Africa; The elder Mzimba's life is told in the book of his son "Ibali Lobomi Nomsebenzi Womfi, Umfundisi Pambani Jeremiah Mzimba" printed at the Lovedale Institution Press, Lovedale, 1923. Livingstone Mzimba's son was the first South African to graduate in medicine from the University of Witwatersrand. Recent advice indicates that after a brief practice in Capetown, young Mzimba has moved to England on the ground that there were no longer any opportunities for himself or for the education of his children. Reverend Livingstone Mzimba died in 1956

name: Fuller, Solomon Carter
misc card notes: Freshman coll; graduated AB 1893; 1894-reported a student in Brooklyn Medical College; 1894-95: student, Howard Medical School; 1898-1899: student in Harvard Medical school; M.D. Boston University 1897: in faculty, Boston Univ. Neurologist Psychiatrist; Attended Liberia College; See also Walls, "Joseph Charles Price" p.150: referred to as "protege," and as "Livington's most famous protege." Also, a Liberian named Moor, came with Fuller: died here, body was sent back; "Who's Who of the Colored Race," ed. by Frank Lincoln Mather. Publ by the author, Chicago, 1915; Solomon Carter Fuller: born, Monrovia, Africa. Aug 11, 1872: son of Solomon C and Ana (Jones) Fuller: AB Livingstone, 1893: MD Boston U School of Medicine, 1897: Pathologist, Westboro State Hospital; Assoc. prof. neurology, Boston Univ.: Director, Psychiatry, Westborough State Hosp.
